{"focus":{"id":"98ff367c-5a9e-58fa-8957-e1d04da2816c","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d30e1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.OA.B.2","description":"Fluently add and subtract within 20 using mental strategies. By end of Grade 2, know from memory all sums of two one-digit numbers.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"OA","cluster":"2.OA.B","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"0eb3e5dd-ea32-5ff9-9b5c-9806c54bbbdc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dd100-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.2","description":"Solve addition and subtraction word problems, and add and subtract within 10, e.g., by using objects or drawings to represent the problem.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b2e2c061-29b5-5946-be19-19e1a5e8e148","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e93c4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.3","description":"Decompose numbers less than or equal to 10 into pairs in more than one way, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record each decomposition by a drawing or equation (e.g., 5 = 2 + 3 and 5 = 4 + 1).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"9dfd6529-b354-556c-9f2a-3d278234cae4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f318e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.4","description":"For any number from 1 to 9, find the number that makes 10 when added to the given number, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record the answer with a drawing or equation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ec423f7c-3e67-5b0c-9f72-c5fd236b2b61","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fc478-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.5","description":"Fluently add and subtract within 5.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"b978b10f-234d-5964-89ed-c132adc07a1f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ca104-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.OA.A.1","description":"Represent addition and subtraction with objects, fingers, mental images, drawings, sounds (e.g., claps), acting out situations, verbal explanations, expressions, or equations.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"OA","cluster":"K.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"6e056208-42cb-524f-bfcf-793bffdaf9a0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba250cd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.CC.B.4.c","description":"Understand that each successive number name refers to a quantity that is one larger.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"CC","cluster":"K.CC.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"aa0c5592-b771-525d-a9a4-e7579b266e1f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fd4e5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.C.6","description":"Add and subtract within 20, demonstrating fluency for addition and subtraction within 10. Use strategies such as counting on; making ten (e.g., 8 + 6 = 8 + 2 + 4 = 10 + 4 = 14); decomposing a number leading to a ten (e.g., 13 - 4 = 13 - 3 - 1 = 10 - 1 = 9); using the relationship between addition and subtraction (e.g., knowing that 8 + 4 = 12, one knows 12 - 8 = 4); and creating equivalent but easier or known sums (e.g., adding 6 + 7 by creating the known equivalent 6 + 6 + 1 = 12 + 1 = 13).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"6f455e8e-dcc3-5836-8926-5a726e009306","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e0fbe-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.B.3","description":"Apply properties of operations as strategies to add and subtract.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"3aa19a18-9443-5552-899b-063648313211","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ebb03-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.B.4","description":"Understand subtraction as an unknown-addend problem. *For example, s